body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Simply run Yosys on the following Verilog file:
```Verilog
module Example;

    parameter FLAG = 1;
    wire [3:0] inp;

    reg out1;
    initial out1 = FLAG ? &inp[2:0] : &inp[4:0];

    reg out2;
    initial
        if (FLAG)
            out2 = &inp[2:0];
        else
            out2 = &inp[4:0];

    wire out3;
    assign out3 = FLAG ? &inp[2:0] : &inp[4:0];

    wire out4;
    generate
        if (FLAG)
            assign out4 = &inp[2:0];
        else
            assign out4 = &inp[4:0];
    endgenerate

endmodule
```

## Expected behavior

Given that all of the conditions in this example are constant expressions, I would expect Yosys to not generate any warnings for any of the out of range accesses (`&inp[4:0]`).

## Actual behavior

Yosys does not generated any warnings for the uses in the `else` branches. However, warnings are generated for the unevaluated operands of the ternary expressions. Is this behavior deliberate? If the ternaries had used non-constant expressions, then warnings should of course be generated.

